      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If you see three sharps (F#, C#, and G#), you can find the key by looking at the **last sharp** on the circle. In this case, the last sharp is **G#**, which tells you the key is **A Major**.\n\nHere is the quick trick: Take the last sharp and go up a half-step (one semitone) to find the tonic. Since G# is the last sharp, moving up a half-step lands you on **A**. Therefore, the key is A Major.\n\nIf the piece were in the relative minor key, you would look at the same spot but go down a minor third (three half-steps) from that last sharp. From G#, going down three half-steps lands you on **F#**, so the relative minor would be **F# Minor**.\n\nThis works because the circle is built so that every time you add a sharp, you are moving to a new key that shares those specific notes. The \"last\" sharp added is always the leading tone (the second-to-last note) of the new key, making it the easiest clue to spot.",
